The Harren Charter is one of several dozen frontier grants issued during the Lantern Reforms period, all following the same structural template: private authority, registry obligation, revenue sharing, charter review.
The template was designed to be administratively cheap: Midgaard gained governance reach without deploying administrative staff to frontier territories.
The charter review mechanism — suspension of rights during registry gaps — was the enforcement tool that replaced direct administrative oversight.
In practice, charter review was rarely invoked: frontier houses maintained registries because the revenue rights depended on them, creating self-enforcing compliance.
The Harren Charter's burial lease provision became a model for subsequent charters in areas with contested prior use — the tribunal ruling in Harren's favor established that chartered authority superseded pre-charter customary rights within defined boundaries.
Midgaard's Continuity faction cites the burial lease tribunal ruling as correct charter law; the Reckoning faction cites it as an example of charter law being used to extinguish rights that predate the charter system entirely.
The passage road maintained under Harren's charter is a functional piece of Midgaard's road warden network; the road's maintenance is one of the few Harren Charter obligations that benefits travelers outside House Harren's direct interests.

