Kowloon's Courier Lantern Office maintains records of passage-tax payments from Harren Charter territory — through-traffic moving between Midgaard's northern routes and Kowloon's supply network passes through the Thornwood corridor.
The passage tax adds cost to the northern timber and ore shipments that Kowloon's harbor processes; the Harbor Syndics have formally complained twice about the Harren Charter's tax rate relative to the road maintenance provided.
Both complaints were resolved by Midgaard's tribunal in Harren's favor, citing the charter's unambiguous authority over passage through its territory.
Kowloon's Harbor Syndics have since routed some northern freight through alternative paths to avoid the Harren passage tax; the alternative routes add travel time but remove the tax obligation.
The routing shift has reduced Harren Charter passage revenue and is the subject of an ongoing dispute in which Harren claims the alternative routes were specifically developed to circumvent the charter — a claim Kowloon denies.
Kowloon views the Harren Charter as an example of how frontier grants create private revenue bottlenecks that private interests maintain against public routing efficiency.

