Kiess's legal scholarship uses the Harren Charter's burial lease tribunal ruling as the canonical example of charter law extinguishing pre-charter customary rights.
The ruling is cited in Kiess's founding charter's anti-sealed-warrant doctrine not as precedent to follow but as precedent to explicitly repudiate: Kiess's charter states that "no charter issued under Midgaard authority shall supersede custodial rights over burial ground within Kiess's founding territory."
The specificity of the Kiess charter's burial-ground exception was written because Kiess's founding territory included cemetery ground from Evermeet's population — territory where the Harren ruling's logic would otherwise apply.
Kiess's Syndic Council holds the original burial registry from Evermeet's population as a civic document, not as a leased asset — a direct institutional rebuke to the Harren Charter's burial-lease framework.
Frontier risk doctrine in Kiess treats the Harren Charter template as an example of governance architecture that creates private incentives misaligned with public goods: the road maintenance obligation is the one civic benefit, and it is the one obligation that is most consistently performed.

