Rakuen has no frontier grants from Midgaard; Rakuen's political status as an external city has prevented the charter grant mechanism from applying to its territory.
The Harren Charter template is studied in Rakuen's Bloom Council as an example of what Midgaard's governance reach looks like when it is extended: private authority, registry obligation, revenue sharing, and charter review.
The Compact Purist faction cites the Harren Charter as evidence that Midgaard's governance extension benefits Midgaard's revenue interests more than frontier populations' welfare.
The Assimilation League faction counters that Harren's charter template, however imperfect, creates formal registry obligations that provide legal standing to territory that would otherwise have none.
Rakuen's Quiet Separatists note that the Harren Charter alternative — no charter, no governance reach, no registry — describes Rakuen's current institutional position, and that the question is whether the charter template's costs are worse than the absence of institutional standing.
Rakuen's Garden Ledger Clerks have proposed a modified Harren Charter template that would give Rakuen registry integration without the burial-lease and passage-tax revenue-sharing components; Midgaard's Charter Sovereignty office has not formally responded.

