Mafdet's Ledger Houses have no jurisdiction over inland frontier grants and no formal position on the Harren Charter.
The passage taxation model in the Harren Charter has a maritime analogue in Mafdet's harbor tariff system — private authority over a chokepoint, public registry obligation, revenue sharing with the overseeing institution.
The analogue ends at the burial lease: maritime law has no equivalent to charging fees for access to graves, and Mafdet's Ledger Houses find the burial-lease component of the Harren Charter among the more difficult aspects of inland charter law to incorporate into maritime legal frameworks.
The Swift Court's standard cargo contract includes a clause exempting maritime cargo from inland passage taxes where alternative sea routes exist — a provision that was partly motivated by early experience with Harren-style toll structures on overland freight.

